<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="66">
[[ Genus 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus Gill</taxonomicName>
]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="66">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="66">
The traditional “working diagnosis” of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
was based strongly on meristics, especially on the high number of dorsal and anal fin elements, with formulae D. XVII-XX,8-11 and A. VII-XII,6-9. There have been also morphometric attributes, albeit rather general: the pectoral fin reaching or exceeding the anal fin origin; body somewhat deep; snout short, mouth rather small, maxilla not reaching the orbital rim, neither vertically nor horizontally; teeth in the outer row subequal in size anteriorly in both jaws (Regan 1905; Kullander 1996; Greenfield &amp; Thomerson 1997; Miller et al. 2005). No synapomorphies were known for 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
, but some of these traditionally diagnostic characters have turned out to be synapomorphic, e.g. the number of anal-fin spines for 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
; others, as expected, were convergent, e.g. the length of the maxilla (Schmitter-Soto, in press). Still others, such as body depth, are useful for alpha-level taxonomy, but not for phylogeny reconstruction (Zelditch et al. 2005).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="67" pageNumber="66">
Allgayer (2001) had already expressed the view that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
should be restricted to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centrarchus">Ar. centrarchus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinosissimus">Ar. spinosissimus</taxonomicName>
. Burgess (2000) judged that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="multispinosus">Ar. multispinosus</taxonomicName>
should be added too, and Allgayer (2001) 
<pageStartToken pageNumber="67">himself</pageStartToken>
included 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
in his subtribe Archocentrina (= 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amatitlania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amatitlania</taxonomicName>
+ [
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
without 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Cr. panamensis</taxonomicName>
], a group for which Schmitter-Soto [in press], found no support). This opinion, although only recently published explicitly, is a venerable one: Regan (1908) called 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
“evidently closely allied” to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
. Other authors, e.g. Bussing (1976), have considered 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
“derived” from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="66" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="67">
However, most molecular phylogenetic hypotheses (Martin &amp; Bermingham 1998; Farias et al. 2004; Hulsey et al. 2004; Concheiro 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2007 -all based on the cytochrome b gene) have found 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
quite unrelated from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
and allies. A possible explanation for this pattern may lie on the intrinsic limitations of cytochrome b. As stated by Martin &amp; Bermingham (1998), “ heroine cichlids… are unfortunately refractory to phylogenetic inference using cytochrome b sequences.” Long branches are common in “dwarf” Neotropical cichlids, such as species of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
and allies, and the cytochrome b gene presents saturation at third-codon position (Farias et al. 2004). Other genes should provide interesting independent evidence to settle the issue.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="67">
My understanding of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
diverges from Allgayer’s (2001), who included also what is here called 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amatitlania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amatitlania</taxonomicName>
, and excluded 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Cr. panamensis</taxonomicName>
. On the other hand, Kullander (2003), who did not recognize 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
, decided to call this species 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Archocentrus panamensis</taxonomicName>
, recognizing that its affinities do not lie with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E80528E6-4EC5-48D2-9B49-38E85C7886AF" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Neetroplus</taxonomicName>
(nor with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amatitlania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigrofasciata">Am. nigrofasciata</taxonomicName>
had been considered a 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:273F29E5-91F4-45BE-8447-659BDE8939E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Cryptoheros Allgayer 2001" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cryptoheros</taxonomicName>
by Allgayer (2001) and an 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
by Kullander (2003).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E80528E6-4EC5-48D2-9B49-38E85C7886AF" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Neetroplus</taxonomicName>
has had a rather unfortunate usage history. Based on a very distinctive but overrated dental character (like the tricuspid teeth of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4B9BCDD6-7318-4D82-B13F-E89502F50F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herotilapia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Herotilapia Pellegrin 1904:(165) 247" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Herotilapia</taxonomicName>
), monotypic at first, it became an artificial group with the inclusion of several incisor-toothed cichlids, such as 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A6E61CB3-96A1-496F-BF62-312ED4C6D0C2" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus carpintis Jordan &amp; Snyder 1899:146" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carpintis">N. carpintis Jordan &amp; Snyder, 1899</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Herichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carpintis">Herichthys carpintis</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:18131267-24B7-479F-824F-C80F8D0703F0" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus bocourti Vaillant &amp; Pellegrin 1902:85 [1]" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bocourti">N. bocourti Vaillant &amp; Pellegrin, 1902</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cichlasoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bocourti">‘Cichlasoma’ bocourti</taxonomicName>
), and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:2411EEF8-6445-445C-AFA1-B6C5A08A5161" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus panamensis Meek &amp; Hildebrand 1913:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">N. panamensis</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panamensis">Cr. panamensis</taxonomicName>
). Among this assemblage, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">H. nematopus</taxonomicName>
is the only species to have incisor teeth as juvenile (Rogers 1981).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="67">
The synonymization of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E80528E6-4EC5-48D2-9B49-38E85C7886AF" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Neetroplus</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
has the disadvantage of obliterating a widely used name (
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6D4EDCB3-9A89-4702-A37B-4B203C5A2EE2" authority="Günther, 1867" authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1867" class="Teleostei" family="Cichlidae" genus="Neetroplus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Neetroplus nematopus Günther 1867:603" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">Neetroplus nematopus</taxonomicName>
). However, a classification should also convey information about phylogeny, and this purpose is not served well by recognizing two monotypic sister genera instead of calling their clade by just one generic name. An example of this stance is the synonymization of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C2F2D5C0-62DA-4FC4-85BE-C3214B17F216" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinodontidae" genus="Garmanella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Garmanella Hubbs 1936:218" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Garmanella</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CC1B2940-9BCF-4EFE-9D61-98754E8B6AEC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinodontidae" genus="Jordanella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Jordanella Goode &amp; Bean 1879:117" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Jordanella</taxonomicName>
(Cyprinodontidae), in “…the interest of having generic categories define derived groups, rather than recognize individual differences…” (Parenti 1981). Moreover, the sister-group relationship of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nicaraguensis">H. nicaraguensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">H. nematopus</taxonomicName>
is supported by most proposed phylogenies (e.g. Martin &amp; Bermingham 1998; Hulsey et al. 2004; Concheiro 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2007).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="67">
It should be acknowledged that a classification alternative to the one here proposed, and equally congruent with the phylogeny presented by Schmitter-Soto (in press), might include all species dealt with in this work in the genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7A9BA3FB-1462-4C73-A40A-F9A660B3AA90" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypsophrys</taxonomicName>
(or 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:60986D0C-086A-4E68-8914-90992063465B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Amphilophus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Amphilophus Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Amphilophus</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Parachromis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parachromis</taxonomicName>
, all three names having been proposed in the same work, on the same page -Kullander &amp; Hartel 1997). It is my opinion, notwithstanding, that the classification proposed here is more informative, and also less disruptive with recent usage. On the other hand, since the aim of this work is to review the species formerly assigned to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Archocentrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Archocentrus</taxonomicName>
, the choice of taxa was not ideal for such higher level decisions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="68" pageNumber="67">
I follow the Evolutionary Species Concept (ESC). However, the ESC is not an operational concept; to be able to recognize species under the ESC (i.e., every lineage that “maintains its identity from other such lineages and which has its own evolutionary tendencies and historical fate”: Wiley 1978), I applied here both the “autapomorphic” and the “diagnosable” versions of the Phylogenetic Species Concept (PSC) (Mayden 1997): every species should display at least one derived character of its own (Rosen 1979), but, if a non-homoplastic (unique) autapomorphy is not found, then “the smallest diagnosable cluster of individual organisms within which there is a [presumed] parental pattern of ancestry and descent” (Cracraft 1983) is to be recognized as a species. Thus, I agree with Lucena et al. (1992), who point out that “to consider two distinguishable populations 
<pageStartToken pageNumber="68">as</pageStartToken>
a single species [implies] loss of information about phylogeny and biogeography.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="68">
The phylogeny and biogeography of the species formerly assigned to 
